3) Evaluation and choice:
- Abbey Road (Rock; Progressive; Progressive Rock) is a classic studio album by The Beatles (1969) known for its meticulous production (George Martin), the well-regarded side-B medley that creates a continuous listening experience, strong sonic characterization of individual instruments and vocal arrangements, and historical significance. These are concrete attributes that make it especially appealing to someone who values the CD format as an album-oriented medium and who wants a coherent, high-quality listening session. Many CD reissues and remasters of Abbey Road are also noted for good mastering, which matters to a CD listener who appreciates sound quality and album flow.
- The Very Best of Prince (Pop; Dance Pop) is a compilation/greatest-hits collection that gathers many excellent singles and showcases Prince's pop and dance-oriented work. It is very popular and contains standout tracks, but as a compilation it spans different recording periods and production approaches. For a listener prioritizing a cohesive album experience and consistent studio presentation on a single CD, a hits compilation typically lacks the deliberate sequencing and single-studio-era production unity that make albums like Abbey Road especially satisfying on CD.
Because my explicit stated preference is simply enjoying CDs, and because that implies valuing the album-format listening qualities (cohesion, production, sequencing, and sound quality) that Abbey Road exemplifies, I select Abbey Road. I reject The Very Best of Prince not because the music is inferior — it contains many excellent songs — but because as a compilation of singles it is less aligned with the album-focused qualities that a CD enthusiast who "enjoys listening to CDs very much" is likely to value.

